description.text:
Custom jello shots! Or ice cubes. Or popsicles. Or candy. Or whatever.

Printed with the Flexion Extruder.

This relies on the layer lines to form a sort of labyrinth seal to be water-tight. It does hold water, but you will need to make sure that there is a tight fit between sides A and B. It also helps to apply some pressure (thus the clamp). The mold itself didn't come apart well and I lost the finer features of the bomb. I recommend coating the mold in cooking oil to help the release. For more details about the design and general consideration when making molds from flexible filaments, see this post.

Make sure your material is food safe before you make anything edible in this mold. Ninjaflex and Semiflex are not safe to be in contact with items intended for consumption. ExcelFil TECH Flex by Voltivo appears to be food safe, but read the MSDS thoroughly before using it for food application

Use a good flexible filament extruder to get accurate, fast printing without blobs and voids.

title: DIY LED Worklight - Convert Spare Lightbulbs into a portable & robust work lamp!

description.text:
I'm turning a school bus into a small house and wasn't happy with the work lights from my local hardware store while I was sanding/scraping the undercarriage in preparation for resealing the chassis/suspension. I have a bunch of E26 LED bulbs (since they never burn out I don't really need to keep spares around...) so I figured it was a waste of $40-50 to buy an LED worklight when I could probably just make one. I'm pretty happy with the result - it's relatively easy to construct and so far seems pretty robust. Requires 5x M6 bolts + 10x locking nuts, an old power cable you can cut up + some 3/4" pvc pipe segments. Oh, and a little bit of soldering wire. Takes less than 10-20 mins or less to construct! Video of me constructing the untested prototype parts:
https://plus.google.com/photos/105317412194765993553/albums/5917024930823811553?authkey=CKnXk_K2mrbWpwE

print the base + psu units + 3 bulb holders at >10% infill + 2 shells. use 15-25mm M6 bolts (5) + 10 locking nuts.  
assemble as shown - and make sure to wrap electrical tape around the exposed metal to avoid electrocution!

description.text:
This is vertical x-axis for the MendelMax 1.5 (or any printer using the same rod distances). It is designed to host the 3-color Diamond Hotend (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:720520) . There is also an provision for adding a SP90 servo mounting to use my Opto-Z-Probe (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:263180). The probe will be attached at the rear - not disturbing any other component and almost invisible when retracted.

The whole thing is a remix of BLNorris "RustySpoon's Vertical X-Axis" (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12434) by adjusting everything for metric nuts, bolts, different nuts for the trapezoidal threaded 8mm rod and other slight modifications. So BLNorris great "RustySpoon" design works now for metrically addicted too!

The belt tensioner is a remix of xavan's "X carriage with belt tensioner" (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:798169) - by the way a really great idea and very easy to use and extremely reliable! Thank you for sharing that idea, xavan!

Several M3-attachment holes for accesories for future modifications and add-ons (like for endstops, LED-lights,...) are already present.

UPDATE

There's now a special to type compact z-probe available: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1476258

It will fit the carriage and the distance between probe and nozzle is just about 1 inch.

title: Laser Reflected Z-Axis Zero-Point Detection Tool

description.text: This is a small clamp designed to clip a low-cost laser pointer onto your open-frame printer chassis.  When used as instructed, you can get your Z-Axis to be at the perfect height before starting any print.

Get a Wal-Mart cheap laser point ($2.47) and clip this to your printers frame in the upper-right corner.  Place the rubber laser button into the cradle and rotate the laser in place until the cradle pushes against the button.  
With the printer bed hot, and the printhead hot, press the home button.  Once the head is at home, adjust the laser so that the beam bounces off your bed and onto the ceiling - this will amplify all the movements the bed makes.  
Now, while watching the beam spot on the ceiling, press the home button and watch.  If the printhead touches the bed, the bed will move a little bit (mine is mounted on aluminum l-braces with magnets), and this will cause the beam-spot to move.  The movement is amplified so that even slight movements will make a reflection change.  
Adjust your Z-Axis endstop upwards and press home again.  Repeat until this is little or no moment.  
Then print and see how your first layer works out.

comments.text: Remember to keep your head hot when doing the alignment - otherwise you might get unwanted deflection from hardened plastic on the tip of the hot-end.  This first layer on this print was unbelievable - no curl at all (small part) and perfect height..

title: MPCNC - Totem Corner Parts Remix to make it Parametric

description.text:
Update 5/30/2017
This is untested, but matches the 525 offsets between the X & Y EMT. Added a middle joiner plate 525-C version STL file:
totem_JoinerPlate_C525_Remix_Rev8.stl
In the openscad file I changed these 2 lines to create this version
Line 33
EMT_Z_Offset = 2-.8;

Line 117
Chamf_Y = 10.9;

Originally, I was looking at the tall corner remix I did, but decided to take a look at making this design parametric since it has a lot of similarities. The downside of this design is you cannot print it on its side like the original design & you have to use long bolts.

Here is what I changed from this design.

  1. Used copyright of original MPCNC design
  2. Made it 1 openscad parametric file for all the parts, except for flex foot.
    (For my Flex foot parametric file see: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1401177)
  3. Outside rounds are consistent width from the 4 vertical holes.
  4. Added a chamfer to the lengths of the EMT cuts
  5. Option to drill hole thru center of part to use less plastic
    (Not sure this is good idea for the Joiner part, but maybe good idea for Top & bottom Part)
  6. Located origin at the center bottom of part
  7. Spacing between pipes of totem design is slightly different from original design.
    (I measure the original design as being 27.6, totem design measures 27.73mm)
  8. I made the US EMT diameter 23.6mm which is what was used in original design

The limit switch portion of the file, I took from this remix I did earlier:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1406498

For the belt tensioning part of the Belt plate see this part:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1402584 I am really happy with the change I made with the bolt connecting above the belt & belt is inline with the belt travel. It is also easy to attach belt & adjust tension.

I created the STL files using the same heights as the original totem design, so it should match that except for the outside rounding diameter & spacing between the pipes on the joiner part is .13mm different which probably was not noticeable, but was different from original design.

I have also included the openscad file which lets vary a lot of the dimensions. You should be able to make US or IE versions of the parts with the openscad file. I only include STL files for US version. See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1104847 for info on this totem design.

There are quite a few variables you can change, but the main ones to look at are:

EMT_OD (Diameter of Pipe)
Totem_Type (Type of part to print)
Thk (Thickness of plastic below or above Pipe on top & bottom part,)

The variable to change between the US & IE is:
EMT_OD = 23.6; //Use 25 for IE

The variable to change to print the part you want is:
Totem_Type = -1; //-1 = Assembled
//1 = Totem Top and Bottom Part
//2 = Totem Joiner Part
//3 = Cover
//4 = Spacer Plate
//5 = Belt Tensioner Plate
//6 = Limit Switch Top Plate

The THK variable is the thickness of plastic for the top & bottom plate beneath or above the horizontal EMT.

You also might want to adjust any of the variables with M5 preceding them. These are related to the bolts. Most of the variables should be documented.

This is a fish puzzle that can be printed or laser cut. Instructions are included to put the fish together. Print without rafts and supports.

Fish can be printed in all together in one setting using the "Fish-ALL Pieces.stl". You may have to play around with the height of print in your slicing program to get the perfect fit, if not, super glue works fine!

Fish can also be printed in different parts using all the "Piece" files or a combination of HeadTail and Body files. To get the flowy and bent fins, print the Body-2mm file and two of the HeadTail-1mm file. For the HeadTail print, while the printer is cooling down (if you have a heated build-plate), begin to carefully bend the fins according to your liking (be cautious of how hot the build-plate is!). Another method is to reheat the plastic and bend.

I printed on both an Ultimaker 2 and a Makerbot Replicator 2. The bigger the size, the better the puzzle will be, otherwise you will need to play with the height of the print to find the perfect fit.

description.text:
In downtown Sioux Falls, SD is a handsome red brick business building known as the Peck-Norton-Murray Building. It was designed by the architect Wallace L. Dow. Dow was influential in the local area and drew up the plans for many stunning buildings in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. His preferred architectural style was Richardsonian Romanesque. This particular building follows a rival-modified version of the same style.

There are two arched doorways between the sidewalk-level storefronts that lead up to the second floor. Atop the brick columns flanking each door are these overlooked beautiful terra-cotta capitals, in a kind of modified Corinthian order.

Considering the harsh climate of the Dakotas and the Upper Midwest in general, it is a lucky thing they've lasted well over 100+ years now!

I snapped about 100 photographs of this capital. I started with the easy shots, holding the camera and aiming up from the sidewalk. Once I was satisfied I had enough photos covering the capital from below, the challenging part began.

I brought out my telescoping painter's pole and attached my Pentax to it, then proceeded to carefully aim it and fire it with a remote. It wasn't easy as I'm out of shape, my arms got sore fast and my Pentax would sometimes refuse to fire. It also drew plenty of looks from passersby! Ha!

Once I decided I probably had enough photos from level and above the capital, I went home. I took all the photos in DNG format to maximise the amount of information captured. I then matched the exposures and tones across all the photos and checked them for sharpness, clarity, etc. I threw out the photos that wouldn't be useful and exported the remaining 78 photos into 8-bit TIFs for Agisoft Photoscan to work with. I kept all the EXIF data intact when exporting via Adobe Lightroom with the exception of the location (I'm one of those anal-retentive types who actually goes to the trouble of attaching location data to every photo)!

I then set Photoscan to work. I used the medium setting at all stages as I didn't feel that I had captured the capital very well yesterday. When I capture it with better photographs, I'll likely try for the high setting and see if it is dramatically different or not.

title: Rostock Max Easy Flexible filament upgrade

description.text:
After many struggles with flexible filament on my Rostock Max Bowden printer, I've come up with the best and easiest solution i've come across.
I found that the filament keeps curling up inside the pneumatic push-fit coupler, which has a 2.4mm inside diameter. Therefore I've designed this easy modification to ensure the inner diameter from extruder all the way to the nozzle is nowhere larger than 2mm.

Follow these steps:

  • First order a E3D embedded bowden coupler: http://e3d-online.com/Embedded-Bowden-Couplings-For-Metal-1.75mm-Filament
  • Print this thing.
  • Drill the small hole with a 2 mm drill to ensure a smooth interior. (you may drill the outer hole with a 8mm drill if the bowden coupling doesn't fit)
  • Apply this modification: http://forum.seemecnc.com/viewtopic.php?f=35&t=5298
  • Replace the aluminum bowden adapter with this printed one.
  • Push the embedded bowden coupler into this printed bowden adapter.
  • Push your bowden tube into the embedded bowden coupler.

Then print all the ninjaflex and semiflex you want without failure!
I've succesfully printed at 25mm/s, about half of the normal PLA print speed. You can also play around with retraction with this modification, no worries about jamming or curling anymore! Normal materials also print perfectly with this mod so you don't need to switch extruders when changing filaments.

description.text:
This is your basic centrifugal "blower" fan, using the motor from an old PC fan. The blades' center hole is 39.35mm in diameter, sized to press-fit over the motor/hub from a Coolmax 8015M12S ND1 fan (after removing the blades and sanding it down smooth).

There's a shallow indentation in the inside-bottom of the main housing, into which the motor should fit after trimming.

The whole thing is about 18.8 mm thick after assembly, and the mounting holes are patterned to match those found on a common 80 mm axial fan (though I don't know what the correct hole pattern would actually be for a blower this size). You'll have to scale/adjust the blades in your model editor if you need to fit a different hub.

This Thing includes both true "squirrel cage" blades and a sort of hybrid version based on the blades from a dead laptop fan. In both cases, they are "backward-inclined" blades, when assembled as in the second photo. You can also (after some sanding) press the blades on "upside down" (with the support ring inward), making it a "forward-inclined" fan, but I am not sure how the performance will differ from the "backward" arrangement, in practice.

The fan inlet is 63.3 mm in diameter, and the outlet measures about 20 x 15.4 mm inside, 24.2 x 18.8 mm on the outside.

Assembly:

  • Find a fan similar to the one described above. If you have a sufficiently-full junk box, this shouldn't be hard. :-)
  • Break the four spider bits on the back that hold the hub/motor to the main fan housing, and discard the housing.
  • Remove the brand/model label from the back of the motor. Save it for later, or perhaps affix it to the outside of the squirrel cage fan's base.
  • Trim the edges of the remaining plastic so that it's as round as possible - or at least, nothing sticks out past the actual round parts of the motor's base.
  • Remove the old blades from the donor hub and carefully scrape and sand it down smooth. It should be 39.20 mm in diameter after cleanup.
  • Pass the motor's wires through the small hole in the base and glue it to the baseplate.
  • Press the new blades onto the hub, with the narrow support ring toward the top edges of the housing, taking special care to keep everything level and aligned perfectly - give it a spin by hand every so often to make sure. Press the blades almost all the way down, taking care to leave a small, even gap between the blades and the bottom of the housing.
  • Apply power and check for interference/dragging, and if good, glue the cover on.

Included are my original Blender work files. Contained in each file are the three main parts of the fan (each as a solid object), and a second copy of the fan blades as a group of parts that can be modified and then combined using boolean modifiers.

Notes:

Take special care regarding your extrusion rate/flow rate when printing the blades, as you want to avoid the nozzle skipping across them during printing. Consider adding Z lift during travel moves. As these are very thin blades (0.7 mm nominal thickness), your printer will need to be particularly well-calibrated. Use your best filament and a small nozzle size for this (mine's 0.4 mm but smaller would probably have been better). For the centrifugal design, print with the narrow support ring down on the plate. For the squirrel cage blades, print with the wide, flat disc side on the plate. Have a suitable drill bit handy, as you'll probably want to ream the housing's mounting holes out a bit.

Expect to need to do some sanding of the blades' edges and the inside of the housing. There's only about a 1.5 mm gap between the two, much of which gets taken up by normal inaccuracies in the printing process.

I started by drawing a few cylinders in Blender, after taking some measurements of my donor fan. Some scaling here, faces deleted there, more faces added over in that spot, on and on until the base was done. The top cover was just the top edge of the base/housing, copied-pasted-extruded.

For the blades, I used a dead squirrel cage fan as a guide, first drawing one simple, rectangular blade placed right on the edge of and tangent to the hub. Then I tapered the bottom edge toward the center, and added a shorter blade rotated 15 degrees from the first one (held only by the outer support ring). Then just copied and pasted around the hub until I had a full set.

Next I added little reinforcing prisms at the junction between one of the blades and the support ring, then copied and pasted that around.

I then created a second copy (the squirrel cage version) with the blades redrawn from scratch (but all other parts derived from the centrifugal version).

description.text:
Sprockets! Is a board game that I invented a few months ago, and now its finally ready to share with the world!

Rules are simple:
Each player begins with one "Spin Token", and starts at the center of the sprocket of their tokens color.
Roll the die and move your token around the board.
Land on an opposing players' starting space and earn an additional "Spin Token"
Use spin tokens to rotate the board and change the path for all players!
First player to land on all opposing players starting spaces, and then return to their own, wins!

These rules are imperfect I'm sure, so if you come across any odd situations or have ideas for new rules, please share!

You will need to print:
-2 X Tee Sprockets (white)
-2 X Line Sprockets (white)
-5 X Cross Sprockets (one in each player color, and one for center of board)
-4 player tokens (I can't recall which ones I used, but user dutchmogul has some awesome ones that he created for Pocket Tactics!) http://www.thingiverse.com/dutchmogul/about
-1 x 4 sided die (I used the Sphere Dice by user anvil777) http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:676660
-9 x thumb tacks to hold the Sprokcets in place (Sprockets are spaced 68mm center-to-center)
-1 foam mat, mine is 5mm thick craft foam

Note that there is an extra file "Elbow Sprocket". This part can be used as an expansion to the original set. Or you can flip any Sprocket over and get is mirror image. Come up with your own layout to increase difficulty, playing time etc.

Have fun!

comments.text:
Fabulous start to a gaming idea. I'm impressed. I've got a few games under my belt that I may one day release to Thingiverse.
I have a few suggestions for the game.
1) To avoid unfair (dis)advantages of T-sprockets and Bar-sprockets, make them all Plus-sprockets, especially with notions #2 & #3.
2) Forego the Spin Tokens for spinning, and use them as Counters for having arrived at a Players Start Sprocket (as opposed to Start Space). You collect your own when you make it back Home.
3) On the Non-Home sprockets's plus-squares (non-center), add "Spin 90 Left" / "Spin 180" / "Spin 90* Right" / (last one blank for "safety") to be Commanded when a Player lands on them. Since the moves are governed by a Die this would allow a choosable strategy of pathing versus desire to alter the board. Meaning, you might want to go one square out of your way to land on the blank square as opposed to spinning the board to your greater disadvantage.
4) With all these suggested changes, I also suggest that the whole sprocket count as landing on another players "Start". At this time that player would hand over one of his four Tokens to that player. When you get back home and give yourself the fourth Token, you win. Stipulation, of course, is that you cannot give it to yourself until you already have the other three Tokens.

An actual, functioning bifold wallet! I've been using one for months with no damage. I like the clear to see whether or not I have money, but an opaque color could be more discreet.

Printed in Ninjaflex with the Flexion Extruder

We had to add a connector between the two card holder slots to get a smooth vertical wall. Otherwise it bends too much under the nozzle pressure. You can cut that off with scissors pretty easily. Also, a single nozzle width would have been good, but the wall is too tall for that. This has two nozzle widths (0.8mm) and everything holds together really well.

This is a little more difficult to print, so we highly recommend getting a Flexion Extruder and dialing in your settings before you try.

comments.text:
Those are some pretty nice hinges... ;-)
But...
You have two big issues you need to address.
The first is that you have 2 undeclared variables or constants, used when calling the two modules.
The second and more important is the 'shimmering' effect over holes and pockets. This is caused by the fact that OpenSCAD doesn't KNOW that there's not supposed to be a 'skin' there. Basically, OpenSCAD allows walls with a thickness of 0.
Quick example:
difference()
{cylinder(r=10, h=20);
cylinder(r=5, h=20);}
This results in a thick-walled tube with the same issue.
The common way to solve this is to make certain the 'cutout' extends outside the part it subtracts from. Like this:
difference()
{cylinder(r=10, h=20);
translate([0,0,-1])
cylinder(r=5, h=22);}

description.text:
My friend was putting together a Blink ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blink_(comics) ) cosplay costume for the Dallas Comic Con this year and asked if I could help her come up with some Teleportation Shards. Of course I gave it a shot!

We went through several iterations of "bolt" vs "splinter" vs "shard" and I struggled with how best to attached the print to something strong enough to hold, small enough to hide in the hand and big enough to hold batteries and a circuit.

After testing the fit on a PVC pipe and the shape of the shard several times I ended up modifying pmoews (thank you for sharing your work pmoews!) Teaching Aid for Quartz Crystals. I completely ruined the teaching aid part of it by scaling it to all sorts of weird angles and then adding a sleeve to slip fit over a 3/4" PVC pipe.

I printed six in translucent purple (four for the shards and two spares) and then nine or so in translucent white for the quiver. April did an amazing job on her costume! All custom and all perfect!

Print with one perimeter, two bottom layers and one top layer. Use translucent filament if you're going to add lights. I used Atomic Filaments translucent PLA. It worked great!

After printing snap off the " * " on the bottom. The part should slip right over a 3/4" schedule 40 pvc pipe snug enough not to fall off. If you want to add the lights Dremel out a hole at the top of the sleeve and poke the LEDs through.

The LED circuit was made out of scraps in my garage. 6 white LEDs, 1 momentary switch and two AA batteries. I know, I know. I should have a resister in there two but there were enough LEDs in series that the current was limited just enough and I really didn't care about protecting them. The whole thing only needed to last a day to be a success.

After the event I realized I should have bought a cheap flashlight or four from Harbor Freight or Walmart and hacked those apart to hide them in the PVC. They probably would have been brighter and last just as long. There's always next time!

Date, School & Place:
3/04/2016
George Mason University located in Fairfax, Va.
The creation took place in Mathematica for a class project for Math 493 class titled; Math Through 3D Printing.

Background of Object:
German mathematicians August Ferdinand Mobius and Johann Benedict Listing discovered the Mobius strip also known as the Mobius band in 1858. The Mobius strip is special in that an object circling the inside loop would circle twice before reaching the starting point. Cutting the band in certain ways will produce a longer band of the original shape not multiple bands.

I have included pictures from my mathematica file of the base, the frame and both meshed together.

Notes:

Extra support was used for this project.
The print time took about four and a half hours.
The size of the whole object was x:85.74mm, y:99.30mm, z:98.02mm
The feet sizes separate from the whole object were x:20.93mm, y:20.93mm z: 14.80mm
The Mobius size separate from the whole object was x:70.88mm, y:99.30mm, z:88.58mm

Finished product was successful first attempt. Extra Note

Removing raft took approximately half hour using fingers and a pencil.

Summary of Creation and Instructions for Printing

The coding for the Mobius strip was created in Mathematica using a code example of a Monkey Saddle Dual, which was given by the instructor. The Mobius strip has parametric equations different from the Monkey Saddle Dual, which are;
x = [R+scos(1/2t)]cost
y = [R+scos(1/2t)]sint
z = s(sin(1/2t))
The Parametric Equations of the Mobius strip used in the coding were found in Mathematica. The equations were incorporated into the code with the Mobius base being made first and the frame being made second. The gridsteps of the frame were adjusted to add or take away lines and the radius was adjusted for how thick the lines would be. The objects are then combined so that the frame is raised on the Mobius base. This is to give more texture to the Mobius strip. The combined Mobius base and frame rests on top two Cuboctahedrons, which are used as a supports because of the flat faces that they have. The Cuboctahedron was created in Mathematica. Using supports will allow the overall print to stand upright. All three of the STL files are included. I have included the mathematica files of the whole code used for this project.

Putting it together:
The Mobius Base STL file is the first file I uploaded in Makerbot with no immediate modification, then I uploaded the Mobius frame STL file also with no immediate modifications. I then added two supports, which were Cuboctahedrons.

I then selected both the base and the frame shrinking them down to a size that would print around four hours.

I positioned the supports by visually deciding where on the build plate would give the best support for the Mobius strip being sure that the mobius object was slightly embedded in the feet supports.

Lastly I selected the Mobius base and Mobius frame rotating them 90 degrees to lay the object flat.

description.text:
This is my Raspberry Pi 2/3 add-on board for vPiP (Whats vPiP? Its a hanging v plotter control software written in Python and Arduino firmware - it can probably be used for other drawing machines, but its main purpose in life is for use with the vPiP software - https://github.com/brianinnes/vpip).

Update (29/04/2016): Will be continuing testing with the current crop of boards, but have moved master on github to v1.01b which adds a couple of minor fixes and features. Also created a Dev branch for future mods. Currently that includes extra Pi GPIO pins on the SPI/I2C headers and an extra header that breaks out a couple of pins from the Arduino that can be used as a software serial port. Added a picture of the current board in testing to this page.

Update (25/04/2016): Boards are working but there is a comms issue requiring a manual restart of the Arduino for drawings to start. Also a few minor fixes and a couple of changes made for v1.01b on github. Will be continuing to test with the v1.0b boards for now.

Update (19/04/2016): First test batch of 1.0b boards have been manufactured (see pic). Will be assembling a board or two to test everything works as expected.

Update (15/04/2016): There are currently two versions (1.0a & 1.0b), version 1.0b is where efforts are being focused at the moment. It is a HAT spec compliant board but the HAT spec components are optional. Will update when I have some boards to test.

What's a hanging v plotter? Its a drawing machine where a pen is suspended from two strings or chains attached to two motors at the top outer corners of the machine. The pen is moved by lengthening or shortening the strings or chains with the motors.

The hardware is based on http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1394948 but includes a DCtoDC PSU that should in theory power the Pi as well as everything else.
